<subSubSection id="C30D650EBE46FFC8FF55B80F80BD079F" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="116" pageId="4" pageNumber="115" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BA83685BE46FFC9FF55B80F812C033B" blockId="4.[189,363,1876,1902]" box="[189,363,1876,1902]" pageId="4" pageNumber="115">
<heading id="D0E081E9BE46FFC9FF55B80F812C033B" bold="true" box="[189,363,1876,1902]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="4" pageNumber="115" reason="3">
<emphasis id="B963EA97BE46FFC9FF55B80F812C033B" bold="true" box="[189,363,1876,1902]" pageId="4" pageNumber="115">Redescription</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA83685BE46FFC8FF55B8D882E205E5" blockId="4.[189,1399,1923,2020]" lastBlockId="5.[189,1399,265,432]" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="116" pageId="4" pageNumber="115">
HEAD. Clypeus uneven, with groove along the anterior margin. Surface of clypeus provided with large granules densely; 
<emphasis id="B963EA97BE46FFC9FE7EB8FD81F20395" box="[406,437,1958,1984]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="115">slr</emphasis>
reaching to anterior margin of frons. Frons bearing median longitudinal groove to vertex; 
<emphasis id="B963EA97BE46FFC9FED4B892811903B6" box="[316,350,1993,2019]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="115">lsa</emphasis>
narrow, not connecting each other. Granulation of frons sparse, indistinct. Mandibles (
<figureCitation id="132C2A00BE47FFC8FF2EBE52815F0576" box="[198,280,265,291]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="14.[189,232,1876,1902]" captionTargetBox="[196,1386,277,1817]" captionTargetId="figure-18@14.[189,1398,264,1820]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="Fig. 4. Mouth parts and antennae of Georissus spp. A–C. Left maxillae. D–F. Labrum. G–I. Labial palpi. J–L. Left mandibles. M–O. Left antennae. A, D, G, J, M. G. (G.) canalifer Sharp, 1888. B, E, H, K, N. G. (Ni.) granulosus Satô, 1972. C, F, I, L, O. G. (Ne.) japonicus Satô, 1972. Scale bars = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6517962" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6517962/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="116">Fig. 4J</figureCitation>
) relatively small; median lateral margin curving strongly, apex bidentate, mola well developed. Antennae (
<figureCitation id="132C2A00BE47FFC8FEA9BE7781E10513" box="[321,422,300,326]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="14.[189,232,1876,1902]" captionTargetBox="[196,1386,277,1817]" captionTargetId="figure-18@14.[189,1398,264,1820]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="Fig. 4. Mouth parts and antennae of Georissus spp. A–C. Left maxillae. D–F. Labrum. G–I. Labial palpi. J–L. Left mandibles. M–O. Left antennae. A, D, G, J, M. G. (G.) canalifer Sharp, 1888. B, E, H, K, N. G. (Ni.) granulosus Satô, 1972. C, F, I, L, O. G. (Ne.) japonicus Satô, 1972. Scale bars = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6517962" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6517962/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="116">Fig. 4M</figureCitation>
) relatively long; antennomere 4 as wide as antennomere 3, about twice as long as antennomere 3; pubescence of club short. Labrum (
<figureCitation id="132C2A00BE47FFC8FCBDBE1483F2053C" box="[853,949,335,361]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="14.[189,232,1876,1902]" captionTargetBox="[196,1386,277,1817]" captionTargetId="figure-18@14.[189,1398,264,1820]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="Fig. 4. Mouth parts and antennae of Georissus spp. A–C. Left maxillae. D–F. Labrum. G–I. Labial palpi. J–L. Left mandibles. M–O. Left antennae. A, D, G, J, M. G. (G.) canalifer Sharp, 1888. B, E, H, K, N. G. (Ni.) granulosus Satô, 1972. C, F, I, L, O. G. (Ne.) japonicus Satô, 1972. Scale bars = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6517962" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6517962/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="116">Fig. 4D</figureCitation>
) not protruding anteriorly; spines on anterior margin indistinct. Apical labial palpomere (
<figureCitation id="132C2A00BE47FFC8FCDABE2983D605D8" box="[818,913,370,397]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="14.[189,232,1876,1902]" captionTargetBox="[196,1386,277,1817]" captionTargetId="figure-18@14.[189,1398,264,1820]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="Fig. 4. Mouth parts and antennae of Georissus spp. A–C. Left maxillae. D–F. Labrum. G–I. Labial palpi. J–L. Left mandibles. M–O. Left antennae. A, D, G, J, M. G. (G.) canalifer Sharp, 1888. B, E, H, K, N. G. (Ni.) granulosus Satô, 1972. C, F, I, L, O. G. (Ne.) japonicus Satô, 1972. Scale bars = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6517962" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6517962/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="116">Fig. 4G</figureCitation>
) oblong oval, with long spines densely. Galea (
<figureCitation id="132C2A00BE47FFC8FEF9BECD812A05E5" box="[273,365,406,432]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="14.[189,232,1876,1902]" captionTargetBox="[196,1386,277,1817]" captionTargetId="figure-18@14.[189,1398,264,1820]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="Fig. 4. Mouth parts and antennae of Georissus spp. A–C. Left maxillae. D–F. Labrum. G–I. Labial palpi. J–L. Left mandibles. M–O. Left antennae. A, D, G, J, M. G. (G.) canalifer Sharp, 1888. B, E, H, K, N. G. (Ni.) granulosus Satô, 1972. C, F, I, L, O. G. (Ne.) japonicus Satô, 1972. Scale bars = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6517962" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6517962/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="116">Fig. 4A</figureCitation>
) bearing long dense setae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA83685BE47FFC8FF55BE83853F066D" blockId="5.[189,1400,471,568]" pageId="5" pageNumber="116">
PRONOTUM. Half oval, slightly projecting laterally in lateral portion, without 
<emphasis id="B963EA97BE47FFC8FBD5BE8C842305A4" box="[1085,1124,471,497]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="116">sdn</emphasis>
. Lateral margin except anterior portion regularly provided with granules. First half of pronotal disc irregularly bearing foveae and grooves, the second half of disc smooth, but with median longitudinal groove reaching near posterior margin.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA83685BE47FFC8FF53BD3B832406C9" blockId="5.[187,1399,607,669]" pageId="5" pageNumber="116">E LYTRA. Bearing seriate large punctures. Elytral interstices smooth, not highly raised. Humeral bulges distinct, smooth. Lateral ridges on each elytron indistinct.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA83685BE47FFC8FF55BD9F8574068B" blockId="5.[189,1331,708,734]" box="[189,1331,708,734]" pageId="5" pageNumber="116">ABDOMEN. Ventrites sparsely bearing granules. Ventrites 1–2 provided with a pair of ventral teeth.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA83685BE47FFC8FF55BC5D832A0730" blockId="5.[189,1401,773,869]" pageId="5" pageNumber="116">MALE GENITALIA. Aedeagus wide, subparallel-sided. Parameres densely provided with small spines on antero-internal portion, as long as phallobase. Median lobe little shorter than parameres. Basal struts short. Phallobase wide; basal foramen large, but indistinct.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA83685BE47FFC8FF55BCD680BD079F" blockId="5.[189,1398,909,970]" pageId="5" pageNumber="116">FEMALE GENITALIA. Ovipositor relatively elongate to longitudinal portion. Two long setae of gonostylus long.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C30D650EBE47FFC8FF55BCA98398011A" pageId="5" pageNumber="116" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BA83685BE47FFC8FF55BCA981680059" blockId="5.[189,303,1010,1036]" box="[189,303,1010,1036]" pageId="5" pageNumber="116">
<heading id="D0E081E9BE47FFC8FF55BCA981680059" bold="true" box="[189,303,1010,1036]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="5" pageNumber="116" reason="3">
<emphasis id="B963EA97BE47FFC8FF55BCA981680059" bold="true" box="[189,303,1010,1036]" pageId="5" pageNumber="116">Remarks</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA83685BE47FFC8FF55BB7B81B7009D" blockId="5.[189,1401,1056,1224]" pageId="5" pageNumber="116">
This subgenus is distinguished by the following characteristics: lacking 
<emphasis id="B963EA97BE47FFC8FBF9BB7B847D006F" box="[1041,1082,1056,1082]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="116">sdn</emphasis>
(present in 
<taxonomicName id="4C174D06BE47FFC8FB2FBB7A8523006F" box="[1223,1380,1057,1082]" class="Insecta" family="Georissidae" genus="Georyssus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="136" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Neogeorissus">
<emphasis id="B963EA97BE47FFC8FB2FBB7A8523006F" box="[1223,1380,1057,1082]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="116">Neogeorissus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); posterior portion of pronotal disc smooth, with median longitudinal groove (uneven, with granules or depression in other subgenera); elytral interstices smooth, not highly elevated (in contrast to uneven, granulated in other subgenera); parameres provided with small dense spines on the anterior portion (even in other subgenera).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA83685BE47FFC8FF55BBB58398011A" blockId="5.[188,1399,1262,1359]" pageId="5" pageNumber="116">
The members of this subgenus are often covered with sand or mud when they are alive (
<bibRefCitation id="EF864B74BE47FFC8FB27BBB58535015D" author="Bameul F." box="[1231,1394,1262,1288]" pageId="5" pageNumber="116" pagination="351 - 356" refId="ref12486" refString="Bameul F. 1989. Description du comportement de camouflage d'un Coleoptere: le deguisement actif de Georissus crenulatus (Coleoptera Georissidae), et proposition d'une nouvelle classification des deguisements chez les invertebrates. Comptes Rendus de l'Academie des Sciences (Paris), Serie III 309: 351 - 356." type="journal article" year="1989">Bameul 1989</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EF864B74BE47FFC8FF56BA4A81250179" author="Shepard W. D." box="[190,354,1297,1324]" pageId="5" pageNumber="116" pagination="121 - 128" refId="ref14207" refString="Shepard W. D. 2003. The biology of Georissus californicus LeConte (Coleoptera, Hydrophilidae, Georissinae). Special Bulletin of the Japanese Society of Coleopterology 6: 121 - 128." type="journal article" year="2003">Shepard 2003</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EF864B74BE47FFC8FE84BA4A82520179" author="Litovkin S. V." box="[364,533,1297,1324]" pageId="5" pageNumber="116" pagination="428 - 432" refId="ref13639" refString="Litovkin S. V. 2018. Contribution to the fauna and bionomy of Georissidae (Coleoptera) of Kyrgyzstan. Euroasian Entomological Journal 17 (6): 428 - 432. https: // doi. org / 10.15298 / euroasentj. 17.6.07" type="journal article" year="2018">Litovkin 2018</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EF864B74BE47FFC8FDC8BA4A82840179" author="Fikacek M." box="[544,707,1297,1324]" pageId="5" pageNumber="116" pagination="251 - 257" refId="ref12979" refString="Fikacek M. 2019. 17. Georissidae Castelnau, 1840. In: Slipinski A. &amp; Lawrence J. F. (eds) Australian Beetles Vol. 2 Archostemata, Myxophaga, Adephaga, Polyphaga (part): 251 - 257. CSIRO Publishing." type="book chapter" year="2019">Fikáček 2019</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation id="EF864B74BE47FFC8FD3DBA4A83C40179" author="Bameul F." box="[725,899,1297,1324]" pageId="5" pageNumber="116" pagination="351 - 356" refId="ref12486" refString="Bameul F. 1989. Description du comportement de camouflage d'un Coleoptere: le deguisement actif de Georissus crenulatus (Coleoptera Georissidae), et proposition d'une nouvelle classification des deguisements chez les invertebrates. Comptes Rendus de l'Academie des Sciences (Paris), Serie III 309: 351 - 356." type="journal article" year="1989">Bameul (1989)</bibRefCitation>
reported that adults of 
<taxonomicName id="4C174D06BE47FFC8FB65BA49856C017E" authorityName="Rossi" authorityYear="1794" box="[1165,1323,1297,1324]" class="Insecta" family="Byrrhidae" genus="Byrrhus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="116" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="crenulatus">
<emphasis id="B963EA97BE47FFC8FB65BA4984E50179" box="[1165,1186,1298,1324]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="116">G</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B963EA97BE47FFC8FB58BA4A856C017E" box="[1200,1323,1297,1323]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="116">crenulatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
attach sand grains to their body surface using oral secretions and their legs.
</paragraph>
